context: Frederick saw <a0_0>Saxony and Polish west Prussia<a0_0/> as potential fields for expansion but <a1_0>could not expect French support<a1_0/> if he started an aggressive war for them. If he joined the French against the British in the hope of annexing Hanover, <a2_0>he might fall victim to an Austro-Russian attack<a2_0/>. The hereditary elector of Saxony, Augustus III, was also elective King of Poland as Augustus III, but <a3_0>the two territories were physically separated by Brandenburg and Silesia<a3_0/>. Neither state could pose as a great power. Saxony was merely a buffer between Prussia and Austrian Bohemia, whereas <a4_0>Poland, despite its union with the ancient lands of Lithuania,<a4_0/> was prey to pro-French and pro-Russian factions. A Prussian scheme for compensating Frederick Augustus with Bohemia in exchange for Saxony obviously presupposed further spoliation of Austria.
